OUR DRIVER HAD LOADED A ROLL OFF BOX WITH ELECTRIC ARC FURNACE DUST. THIS WASTE MATERIAL IS LIKE TALCUM POWDER AND FLOWS VERY EASY.  ONCE THE ROLL OFF WAS LOADED AND TARPED, THE DRIVER TOOK OFF WITH IT. WHEN HE HAD TO BRAKE HARD, THE MATERIAL FLOWED FORWARD, UP UNDER THE TARP AND OUT ONTO ROAD AND FRAME OF TRAILER.  OUR DRIVER WAS UNAWARE OF THE SPILL AND CONTINUED WITH SMALL AMOUNTS BLOWING OFF OF TRAILER.  THE MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP BY THE GENERATOR WHO HAD SEEN THE MATERIAL ON THE ROAD.  WE ARE NO LONGER USING ROLL OFF BOXES W/O HARD TOPS.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: SHIPMENT WAS PLACED ON A SKID, WHICH WAS BLOCKED AND BRACED PROPERLY.  THE DRIVER THAT UNLOADED THE FREIGHT SAID HE USED BARREL FORKS TO LOAD THE DRUMS ONTO ABOVE MENTIONED SKID, PUTTING DOWN CARDBOARD FIRST.  THE PEDDLE DRIVER CLAIMS THE DRUM LOOKED LIKE IT HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY A FORK.
DRUMS WERE FOUND LEAKING AROUND THE SEALS.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED PROPERLY AND THE FREIGHT WAS SENT ONTO DESTINATION.

AS TRAILER WAS BEING UNLOADED IT WAS NOTICED THAT THERE WAS A SMALL PIN HOLE IN THE SIDE OF THE TOTE AT THE SEAM.  IT APPEARS THE SEAM GAVE WAY AND ALLOWED THE CONTENTS TO LEAK.  A CLEAN UP COMPANY WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE TO HANDLE THE SPILL AND THE TOTE WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

WHILE BOX WAS BEING UNLOADED IT WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT BLADE. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED PROPERLY AND THE FREIGHT WAS DELIVERED TO THE SHIPPER.

column168: DURING UNLOADING PROCESS A LEAKING CONTAINER WAS LOCATED IN TRAILER. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED. TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED CLEANUP USING ABSORBENT MATERIALS. column168: UCLX 30085 NOTED EMITTING VAPOR BY CARRIER PERSONNEL. CAR ISOLATED AND CONSIGNEE NOTIFIED. CONSIGNEE REPRESENTATIVE RESPONDED AND FOUND THE VAPOR VALVE CAP LOOSE ALLOWING VAPORS TO ESCAPE. THE PLUG WAS PROPERLY TIGHTENED STOPPING THE RELEASE. ONE CARRIER EMPLOYEE WAS EXPOSED TO PRODUCT VAPORS AND EXPERIENCED NAUSEA AND A HEADACHE. THE EMPLOYEE WAS TRANSPORTED WHERE HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED.

column168: DRIVER PICKED UP 22 BOXES OF BIO-HAZ WASTE FROM CUSTOMER. BOXES APPEARED TO BE IN GOOD ORDER AND WERE PROPERLY CLOSED. DRIVER LOADED BOXES ONTO TRUCK AND CONTINUED ON ROUTE. WHILE STOPPED AT ANOTHER CUSTOMER LOCATION, DRIVER NOTICED 1 BOX LEAKING. DRIVER INSPECTED BOX AND FOUND IT TO BE COMPROMISED DUE TO IMPROPER PACKAGING AND LINER PUNCTURED. DRIVER REPACKAGED THE BOX AND CALLED DISPATCH TO NOTIFY OF INCIDENT. DRIVER CLEANED THE LEAKAGE AND CONTINUED ON ROUTE. DISPATCH NOTIFIED SALES AND SALES CALLED THE CUSTOMER TO INFORM OF SITUATION. CUSTOMER WAS MADE AWARE OF PROPER PACKAGING PROCEDURES IN REGARDS TO TYING THE LINER AND DISPOSING OF SHARPS IN PROPER CONTAINERS.

UPON RETURN TO THE TERMINAL IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE DRUM WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP AROUND THE RING. THE DRUM WAS ISOLATED ON A PALLET AND THE CHEMICAL MANUFACTURES ASSOC. REPORTING PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED. THE DRUM IS CURRENTLY AT THE TERMINAL IN A SECURE LOCATION AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER. THE PICK UP DRIVER WAS COUNSELED TO CHECK ALL HAZARDOUS FREIGHT AT THE TIME OF PICK UP TO ENSURE IT CAN CE TRANSPORTED SAFELY.
NO REMARKS.

TILT DRUM TO SIDE STOP LEAK CONTAINED DRUM OVER PACKED DRUM SENT CONTAINED SPILL CLEANED UP PUT IN ITS PROPER PLACE FOR DISPOSE OF.

THIS PACKAGE WAS DAMAGED DURING THE INBOUND SORT OPERATIONS AT THE FED-ED CGFA STATION.  AFTER THE INITIAL CALL ABOUT THE SPILL, THE DANGEROUS GOODS SPECIALIST CONTACTED DG ADMIN ABOUT BAD PACKAGING INSIDE THE BOX.  THERE WAS INSUFFICIENT CUSHIONING TO PROTECT THE GLASS JARS AND THERE WAS NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL AS REQUIRED BY THE PACKING INSTRUCTIONS FOR LIMITED QUANTITY SHIPMENTS.  MIKE HOYSLER IN DANGEROUS GOODS ADMINISTRATION CALLED THE FAA ABOUT THESE INNER DISCREPANCIES AND THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.  THE FAA DID INVESTIGATE THE SHIPMENT AND AT THE CONCLUSION OF THEIR INVESTIGATION THE SHIPMENT WAS RELEASED TO FED-EX IN ORDER TO OBTAIN PACKAGE DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.

THE  SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE/LEAKAGE OCCURRED.  APPARENTLY THE CAP SEAL ON ONE OF THE INNER PLASTIC UNITS FAILED ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

column62: Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: DURING THE SORT OPERATION IN THE MEMPHIS SORT CENTER OTHER PACKAGES CRUSHED THIS BOX CAUSING SOME OF THE ADHESIVE TO LEAK OUT OF ONE OF THE INNER TUBES.  THE SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST CLEANED UP THE SPILL PER RED-EX POLICY AND PLACED THE BOX IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED IN THE DANGEROUS GOODS HOLD AREA UNTIL FINAL SHIPMENT DISPOSITION IS OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER.

THIS PACKAGE BEGAN GIVING OFF A DIESEL FUEL ODOR AND GETTING DAMP DURING THE SORT OPERATIONS AT THE FED-EX DENVER RAMP FACILITY.  WHEN THE SPILL CLEAN-UP SPECIALIST INSPECTED THE PACKAGE, HE FOUND THAT THE INNER ITEMS WERE DIESEL FUEL INJECTORS THAT ERE LEAKING DIESEL FUEL FRO THE BAG CONTAINING THE INJECTORS.  THERE WAS NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK WAS OFFERED TO FED-EX.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM PENDING AN INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.  THIS SHIPMENT WS SCHEDULED TO BE INSPECTED BY THE FAA ON 11/04.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DURING THE LOAD OPERATIONS IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THIS PACKAGE CONTAINED A GO-CART GASOLINE ENGINE.  THE ENGINE'S FUEL TANK APPARENTLY HAD GASOLINE IN IT WHICH LEAKED GAS THROUGH THE CAP.  THE OUTER PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED, LABELLED, OR DOCUMENTED TO CONTAIN DANGEROUS GOODS.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. THE FAA OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED ON NOV. 10, 1999.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: THIS PACKAGE WAS NOTICED TO BE LEAKING IN THE VEHICLE DURING THE PICKUP OPERATION.  THE BOX WAS NOT LABELED OR MARKED TO DECLARE IT AS CONTAINING ANY DANGEROUS GOODS PRODUCT, NOR WAS THERE ANY PAPERWORK TO REFLECT SUCH INFORMATION.  THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED AND CLEAN-UP WAS BEGUN.  I WAS CONTACTED AND ATTEMPTS WERE MADE TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER FOR INFORMATION REGARDING THE CONTENTS.  I NOTIFIED THE BNA/CASFO OFFICE OF THE INCIDENT AFTER THE COMMODITY WAS DETERMINED TO BE A REGULATED DANGEROUS GOODS PRODUCT ACCORDING TO THE MSDS.  ALEX EVANS OF THAT OFFICE INVESTIGATION THE INCIDENT. PACKAGE WAS RELEASED BACK TO THE SHIPPER.

WHEN THE SPILL CLEAN-UP SPECIALIST CLEANED UP THE SPILL SHE NOTED THAT THERE WAS A SOLVENT ODOR COMING FROM THE DRUM.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP PER FED-EX POLICY.  THE MSDS WAS SENT TO ME ON 11/04.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED AFTER FINDING THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME OF CORROSIVE LIQUID, N.O.S. IN THE BODY OF THE MSDS.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING AN INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0915 HOURS, THURSDAY, NOVEMBER 4, 1999, WHILE SWITCHING NINE CARS AT THE LPG RACK INSIDE VALERO REFINERY IN PAULSBORO, NEW JERSEY, WPPA-10 DERAILED THREE TANK CARS DUE TO SWITCH POINT BROKEN UNDER MOVEMENT (PRIVATE TRACK, PLANT RESPONSIBILITY). CGTX 68005 CONTAINING LIQUIFIED PETROLEUM GAS DERAILED AND ROLLED 90 DEGREES ON ITS LEFT SIDE. "A" END COUPLER REMAINED ENGAGED TO "A" COUPLER OF SECOND CAR CGTX 63831. THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT. CGTX 63831 CONTAINING LIQUIFIED PETROLEUM GAS ROLLED 90 DEGREES TO ITS RIGHT SIDE, RESTING APPROXIMATELY 15' FROM AN UNDERGROUND PIPELINE OWNED BY SUN PIPELINE. THE "B" END SILL CRACKED, TWISTED, WHILE COUPLED TO "A" END OF GATX 55499. GATX 55499 CONTAINING LIQUIFIED PETROLEUM GAS DERAILED ON THE "A" END. L2 WHEEL DERAILED ON "B" END. THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT. SINCE THE INCIDENT OCCURRED INSIDE THE PLANT FACILITY, THEY EXERCISED EVACUATION OF THE RESEARCH BUILDING AND LOCAL AGENCIES GAVE OPTIONS TO LOCAL RESIDENTS FOR VOLUNTARY EVACUATION. THE THREE TANKS CARS WERE SPOTTED AT THE RACK FOR UNLOADING. THEY ARE AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM VALERO REFINERY.

column168: DRIVER ARRIVED TO DELIVER SHIPMENT TO AMCOT INC.UPON ARRIVAL HE OPENED TRAILER DOOR AND OBSERVED LIQUID RUNNING UNDER PALLET AND DRIPPING FROM SHIPMENT CONSIGNED TO CHOICE USA FROM CAROLINA BEUERAGE. DRIVER OBSERVED IT WAS CORROSIVE LIQUID AND EVACUATED AREA AND SECURED UNIT. DRIVER CALLED DISPATCH WITH INFORMATION CONCERNING ID OF CHEMICAL AND DETAILS HE OBSERVED. DISPATCH NOTIFIED RISK MANAGEMENT DEPT. WITH DETAILS OFSPILLTO SEEK HANDLING INSTRUCTIONS. DISPATCH CONTACTED HEPACO CLEANUP cONTRACTOR AND SHIPPER TO ARRIVE/NOTIFY OF SPILL AND SEEK MSDS SHEET FOR PRODUCT INFORMATION AND CLEANUP PROCEDURES TO UTILIZE. CHEMICAL FOUND TO BE FOOD STUFF SOLUTION DILUTED TO 20% PHOSPHORIC ACID USED TO MFG. CHEERWINE SOFT DRINK. CLEAN UP CREW WAS DISPATCHED TO SCENE OF SECURED UNIT AND USED LIME TO NEUTRALIZE ACID AND ABSORBENT TO SOAK UP SPILLED MATERIAL. DRIVER AND UNIT RETURNED TO INSPECT REMAINDER OF CARGO FOR CONTAMINATION. NONE WAS FOUND AS CARGO WAS ON PALLETS AND LIQUID CHEMICAL DID NOT GET ON OTHER ADDITIONAL PRT. RESIDUE WAS SECURED FOR DISPOSAL AND TRAILER DECONTAMINATED. IT WAS DETERMINED THE CONTAINER WAS PUNCTURED BY A NAIL PROTRUDING ABOVE THE SLAT OF THE PALLET THE CONTAINERS WERE SECURED ON FOR TRANSPORT. THE NAIL HEAD RUBBED THRU THE BOTTOM OF THE POLY CONTAINER OF ACID WHILE MOVING DURING TRANSPORT. EVIDENTLY THE NAIL RUBBED THRU THE CONTAINER CAUSING THE CHEMICAL TO LEAK OUT ONTO TRAILER FLOOR. THE INCIDENT COULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED IF CARDBOARD LINER HAD BEEN PLACED OVER SLATS ON PALLET PRIOR TO PLACING POLY CONTAINERS ONTO THE PALLET BY SHIPPER. THE INCIDENT WAS HANDLED IN COMPLIANCE WITH AAA COOPER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPILL NOTIFICATION PLAN REQUIREMENTS.

DRIVER OWNER SUPERVISION BROUGHT THESE  BOX TO MY ATTENTION AS IT APPEARED TO BE LEAKING.  A PLASTIC WAS PLACED AROUND IT AND IT WAS PUT IN THEHAZ AREA/  I ESNT A MSG TO THE  STATION AND CONTACT THE ILN HJAZ DEPT.  I THEN CALLED THE EMERGENCY NUMBER ONT HE DECS AND RECEIVED  AN MSDS FROM SHIPPER.  THE BOX WAS WET BUT DIDN'T APPEAR TO BE LEAKING ALTHOUGH IT DID SEEM TO HAVE AN ODOR TO IT.  ALL THE PROPER PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED.  ILN SENT US A DRUM AND WE PLACED THE BOX  IN THE DRUM AND PLACED THE PROPER MARKINGS  ON THE DRUM AND DELIVERED IT TO THE RECEIVER.  NO OTHER PACKAGES WERE AFFECTED BY THIS HAZ LEAK AND NO PERSONELL WERE HARMED.

A meeting with the driver and warehouse personnel to go over our dunnage policies and raise the awareness level with our driver that they be inside the trailer if at all possible to assist in the unloading procedure.

CAR WAS TAKEN TO CONTAINMENT PIT AFTER PRODUCT LEAK FROM WELD FRACTURE DISCOVERED AND REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO TANKER TRUCKS. CAUSE OF OVERSPEED IN RETARDER SYSTEM WAS DUE TO TALLOW TYPE PRODUCT RESIDUE ON RETARDERS FROM CAR THAT WAS HUMPED JUST PRIOR TO GATX 55110. THIS RESIDUE PRODUCT WAS CARRIED ON THIS CARS WHEELS AND REDUCED THE RETARDATION OF THE CAR AND GATX 55110. SPILLED PRODUCT IN CONTAINMENT PIT WAS VACUUMED AND TAKEN TO AN ON SITE CLARIFIER. MINIMAL SURFACE STAINING OF TRACKS AND BALLAST WAS FOUND IN BOWL TRACKS. RELEASE WILL BE MONITORED FOR FURTHER REMEDIAL ACTION IF WARRANTED.

column168: DRIVER WAS EN ROUTE FROM MEMPHIS, TENNESSEE TO LITTLE ROCK ARKANSAS ON A FOUR LANE HIGHWAY WHERE THE HIGHWAY CURVED. DRIVER CLAIMS TO HAVE BEEN STARTLED BY A LARGE DEER WHICH RAN ACROSS THE HIGHWAY IN FRONT OF THE TRUCK AND IN REACTION SWERVED THE TRUCK AND LOST CONTROL ROLLING IT OVER ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD. HOURS OF SERVICE RECORDS WERE CAREFULLY RECHECKED THIS DRIVER DROVE 0 HOURS THE PRIOR DAY AND HAD 13.25 HOUR BREAK IN SERVICE HAD TWO DAYS OFF THE DAY BEFORE THAT. FATIGUE WAS NOT AN ISSUE. DRIVER WAS TESTED FOR SUBSTANCE ABUSE AND TEST WAS FOUND TO BE NEGATIVE. DRIVER WAS CITED BY POLICE AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT AND AS RESULT OF VERTEX COMPANY INVESTIGATION HAS BEEN PERMANENTLY DISQUALIFIED/TERMINATED AS VERTEX DRIVER. THIS WAS AN UNDEVELOPED AREA STATE MAINTAINED AT THE SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY NO STREAMS OR OBSTACLES BUT ROLLING TOPOGRAPHY WHICH INTRUDED INTO THE OVERTURN PROTECTION WHICH WAS EMBEDDED INTO THE DIRT/GRAVEL. THE AIR FITTINGS HAD BEEN TORN OFF AND THE SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE 12% BY WEIGHT WAS COMING OUT OF THE ONE INCH HOSE. IT LEAKED UNTIL VERTEX ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AND PLUGGED THE HOLE. LOCAL FIRE PROTECTION DIKED THE AREA AND VERTEX CONTRACTORS REMOVED THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS FROM THE SCENE AND RESODDED. PREVENTION OF  FUTURE INCIDENTS MEETINGS ARE BEING HELD AT ALL VERTEX PLANTS COUNSELING QUICK RESPONSE AND PRIORITIZATION WHILE DRIVING. DRIVERS NOT TO ENDANGER OTHER HUMANS AND THE ENVIRONMENT BY RESPONDING TO ANIMALS ON THE HIGHWAY

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS TRAVELING DOWN HILL WHEN HE OVER CORRECTED ON A TURN WHICH CAUSED THE TRAILERS TO ROLL OVER.  ON THE ROLL OVER THE 1ST TRAIL WE WAS RIPPED OPEN BY BARRICADES AND THE 2ND TRAILER WAS PUNCTURED.  WE PLACED A HAY BALE DAM AT BOTTOM OF HILL TO STOOP THE PRODUCT, WHICH SET UP LIKE A WAX CANDLE IN A MATTER OF MINUTES.  THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED ON THE SOIL WITH NONE SOAKING INTO THE GROUND BECAUSE OF ITS WAXING PROPERTIES.
THE UNLOADER IN THIS CASE USED A FORKLIFT TO PRY UP 2*4'S USE DTO SECURE DRUMS IN PALCE.  BY DOING SO, WENT UNDER THE WOOD TOO FAR AND FORKED THE BOTTOM PART OF THE DRUM WITH THE TINE.

THE 20 DRUM SHIPMENT WAS LOADED ON THE TRAILER WITH ANOTHER SHIPMENT OF A PIECE OF STEEL BEHIND IT.  PLYWOOD WAS USED TO PROTECT THE DRUMS.  THEE DRIVER SID HE MADE A QUICK STOP THAT MAY HAVE CAUSED THE STEEL TO PUNCTURE THE PLYWOOD AND THE DRUM.

column168: THIS PIECE IS ONLY DAMAGED PACKAGE IN THIS 5 PIECE SHIPMENT.  WHEN THE SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST AT THE FEDEX SORT FACILITY IN MEMPHIS PERFORMED HIS SPILL CLEANUP DUTIES, HE NOTICED THAT THE INNER CANS HAD FLASHPOINT INFORMATION ON THEM OF 45 AND 60 DEGREE FLASHPOINTS. KNOWING THAT THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELINGS FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ON THE OUTER BOX, I WAS NOTIFIED ABOUT THIS POSSIBLE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT.  4 OF THE PIECES WERE HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION (1 PIECE HAD BEEN DELIVERED BACK TO THE SHIPPER BY THE ORIGIN STATION BECAUSE OF AN ODOR) IN THE MEMPHIS SORT CENTER.  THEY WILL BE HELD PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.  1 OF THE 4 PIECES IS KNOWN TO BE NON-HAZARDOUS.  NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK WAS OFFERED TO FEDERAL EXPRESS.

PACKAGE WAS GIVEN TO FEDEX AND DURING TRANSIT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  PACKAGE OPENED TO FIND ONE BOTTLE BROKEN AND OTHER PACKAGE INSIDE IDENTIFIED AS "CALDOFIX RESIN KIT"  OTHER ITEMS HAVING NAMES INSIDE THE BOX WERE DUROFIX-2 AND CITOFIX/DUROFX.  SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND PROVIDED AN MSDS WHICH IDENTIFIED A PRODUC OF CALDOFIX HARDENER AS BEING A CORROSIVE LIQUID, TOXIC, NOS (CONTAINS 2,2-DIMETHYL4, 4'-METHYLENE-BIS(CYCLOHEXYLAMINE). PACKING GROUP I. NOT BEING EXACTLY SURE OF THE CONTENTS THE FAA WAS CONTACTED FOR INVESTIGATION AND THE PACKAGE IS HELD PENDING THAT INVESTIGATION.

ON NOVEMBER 8, 1999 AT APPROXIMATELY 1317 HOURS, A RAILROAD TANK CAR, TAZX 1003, LOADED WITH CORROSIVE LIQUID N.O.S. TECHNICAL NAME SODIUM SULFIDE SOLUTIONS SPENT, CONTAINING SODIUM HYDROSULFIDE, WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM A DEFECTIVE MANWAY COVER GASKET, WHILE BEING SWITCHED  AT KCS' ALEXANDRIA, LOUISIANA RAIL YARD.  THE TANK WAS IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED TO AN INACTIVE TRACK TO PREVENT FURTHER MOVEMENT AND POSSIBLE SPILLAGE.  THE SHIPPER (RESPONSIBLE PARTY) WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SITE PROVIDING FOR NECESSARY REPAIRS AND DECONTAMINATION.

column168: WHILE EN ROUTE FROM NEWBURGH, NY TO CHICOPEE, MA DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING FROM TRAILER.  DRIVER PULLED VEHICLE IN TO TRUCK STOP (T/A) IN MILLDALE, CT.  DRIVER PURCHASED CLAY BASED ABSORBENT MATERIAL (SPEEDY DRY) TO ABSORB LIQUID THAT WAS LEAKING FROM TRAILER.  PACKAGING FAILURE/DRUM FATIGUE WAS THE CAUSE OF THE LEAKING DRUM.

THIS IS A SINGLE COMPARTMENT UNBAFFLED TRAILER WITH THREE DOME LIDS. THE CENTER DOME LID IS USED FOR LOADING AND HAS ROLL OVER PROTECTION AND A PRODUCT CONTAINMENT AREA. THE FORWARD AND REAR DOME LIDS ARE USED FOR INSPECTION AND CLEANING. MI INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THIS WAS THE FIRST LOAD THAT ONE OF FOUR WING NUTS USED TO SECURE THE FORWARD DOME LID WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED AND ALLOWED PRODUCT TO LEAK DURING FORWARD SURGES OF THE OIL. NUMBER 4 OIL IS QUITE THICK AND EACH SMALL LEAK SPREAD SLOWLY ACROSS PORTIONS OF THE OTTER SKIN NEAR THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER. NOT NO SINGLE DROP OF OIL FELL FROM THE TRAILER EITHER AT THE SHOULDER WHERE HE STOPPED OR ON THE HIGHWAY FOR PREVIOUS MILE WHERE I INSPECTED. WE TIGHTENED THE LOOSE WING NUT , WIPED OFF THE OIL FROM THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER, AND EMPHASIZE DURING OUR TRAINING PROGRAMS THAT ALL DOME LIDS MUST BE CHECKED ALL THE TIME NOT JUST THE LID NORMALLY USED. THIS INCIDENT WAS DRIVER ERROR AND WAS CAUSED BY EQUIPMENT MALFUNCTION.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0800 NOVEMBER 26,1999, RONALD LANDERS, THE APRIA HEALTHCARE EMPLOYEE INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT WAS MOVING A TRUCK AT THE APRIA BRANCH AT 11224 AUROA AVE. DES MOINES, IA. HE HAD COMPLETED FILLING THE HL 190 BULK CONTAINER CARGO TANK ON THE TRUCK. HE WAS DISTRACTED AND THEN STARTED TO MOVE THE TRUCK, FORGETTING TO DISCONNECT THE FILL HOSE. AS HE PULLED AWAY THE HOSE PULLED THE PIPING LOSS FROM THE VERTICAL TANK, RIPPING A SMALL HOLE IN THE PIPING. THE RIP CAUSED A LEAK WHICH RESULTED IN APPROXIMATELY 750 GALLONS OF OXYGEN, REFRIGERATE LIQUID BEING RELEASED ONTO THE CONCRETE. HE IMMEDIATELY TURNED THE IGNITION OF THE TRUCK OFF AND CONDONED OFF THE AREA TO KEEP VEHICLES AND PEDESTRIANS OUT OF THE AREA. HE THEN ADVISED HIS SUPERVISOR AND THE AREA WAS KEPT SECURED AND UNDER OBSERVATION UNTIL THE OXYGEN DISSIPATED. THERE WAS NO COLLATERAL DAMAGE OR INJURIES.

ONCE WE WERE NOTIFIED WE DISPATCHED OUR INITIAL RESPONSE CLEAN UP CREW AND EQUIPMENT TO THE SCENE. MEMBERS OF OUR SPILL RESPONSE MANAGEMENT TEAM WERE ALSO DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. THEY WORKED IN CONJUNCTION WITH THE PUBLIC AGENCIES ON SITE TO STABILIZE THE SITUATION. AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP COMPANY THAT HAD BEEN SUMMONED TO THE SCENE BY CAL TRANS WAS ENGAGED TO COMPLETE THE CLEAN UP OF THE SITE. THE DRIVER AS A MEMBER OF THE INCIDENT INVESTIGATION TEAM PARTICIPATED IN THE INVESTIGATION AND AGREED WITH TEAMS CONCLUSION AND SUGGESTIONS. HE HAS BEEN COUNSELED AND AN INCIDENT PREVENTION OBSERVATION WILL BE CONDUCTED FOCUSING ON HIS DRIVING. THE IPO WILL BE CONDUCTED BY ANOTHER DRIVER. THE RESULTS OF THE INCIDENT INVESTIGATION HAVE BEEN FORWARDED TO ALL DRIVERS IN THE COMPANY.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE TRAVELING ON INTERSTATE 94 AT THE INTERSECTION OF ROUTE 24 IN TAYLOR, MICHIGAN, THE DRIVER WAS INVOLVED IN A VEHICULAR ACCIDENT, APPARENTLY CAUSING THE TRACTOR TRAILER UNIT TO ROLLOVER.  THREE, THREE HUNDRED AND TWENTY GALLON TOTE TANKS WERE DAMAGED AS A RESULT OF THE ROLLOVER ACCIDENT. APPROXIMATELY EIGHT HUNDRED AND SEVENTY GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED TO THE ASPHALT AND SOIL.  NO WATER WAS AFFECTED.  THE TAYLOR FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE TO INVESTIGATE.  MARINE POLLUTION CONTROL OF DETROIT, MICHIGAN RESPONDED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  APPROXIMATELY THIRTY YARDS OF WASTE WERE GENERATED AND PLACED INTO TWO ROLL OFF BOXES. APPROXIMATELY TWELVE HUNDRED GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS VACUUMED OUT OF THE TOTE TANKS AND PLACED INTO TWENTY-FIVE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUMS. MARINE POLLUTION CONTROL COORDINATED DISPOSAL OF THE ROLL OFF BOXES AND THE RECOVERY DRUMS.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  ALL FEDERAL, STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

PART TIME HAZ MAT SPILL TECHNICIANS RANDY WILLIAMS AND ALAN HENDERSON DONNED PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BROWN FIBREBOARD MARKED AND LABELED AS FOLLOWED: TOXIC SOLID., INORGANIC, N O S., UN3288, TOXIC LABEL, ORIENTATION ARROWS AND CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS.   THERE WAS A BROWN GRANULAR POWDER LEAKING FROM THE BOX.  THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND ONE METAL CAN WITH A SCREW TYPE CLOSURE.  THERE WAS NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURE. THEY SECURED THE CLOSURE, PLACED THE METAL CAN INSIDE A PLASTIC BAG, RE PACKED THE BAGGED METAL CAN INTO THE FIBREBOARD BOX, PLACED THE BOX INSIDE 2 PLASTIC BAGS AND PLACED THE SHIPMENT INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM. THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THE SPILL WAS CLEANED BEFORE NORMAL OPERATION RESUMED.  THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WITH THIS POWDER, SHE DID NOT REQUIRE MEDICAL ATTENTION. GIACONA ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE CAP, BUT THE LEAK DID NOT STOP.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND HIRED GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE TO RESPOND.  UPON ARRIVAL, GARNER DISCOVERED THAT THE PACKING AROUND THE VALVE HANDLE WAS THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  GARNER PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE VALVE TO CATCH ANY SPILLAGE.  THEY DISASSEMBLED THE VALVE AND REPLACED THE PACKING AROUND THE HANDLE. THEY REASSEMBLED THE VALVE AND STOPPED THE LEAK.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR NORMAL MOVEMENT. RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER NOTIFIED CHEMTREC.

ON 11/19/99 AT APPROXIMATELY 510 P.M. ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER, JACK GIACONA, WAS NOTIFIED THAT THE ABOVE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM.  UPON ARRIVAL, GIACONA DISCOVERED A STEADY DRIP COMING FROM THE INTERNAL STEAM HEATER COIL OUTLET PIPE.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  THE SHIPPER WAS ABLE TO TIGHTEN THE CAP AND STOP THE LEAK.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO TRAVEL TO DESTINATION.  UPON ARRIVAL AT DESTINATION, THE CAR WILL BE SENT TO ITS HOME SHOP FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIR. RAILROAD EMPLOYEE, DAVEY BROUGHTON, DISCOVERED AND REPORTED THE LEAK.  BROUGHTON LATER COMPLAINED OF HAVING A HEADACHE.  HE WAS TRANSPORTED TO PARK PLACE HOSPITAL AT THE REQUEST OF SUPERINTENDENT RAY PERRY.  BROUGHTON WAS TREATED AND RELEASED. RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER CONTACTED CHEMTREC.

column168: H.L. BART, REGIONAL MANAGER CTS, WAS NOTIFIED BY W.M. SEABAUGH OF A STRONG ODOR AT THE AVONDALE YARD.  H.L. BART CONTACTED RMCC FOR A STATUS REPORT ON SUBJECT ODOR REPORT.  RMCC PUT H.I. BART IN CONTACT WITH SPECIAL AGENT PAUL MILLER AT THE AVONDALE FACILITY.  MR. MILLER INFORMED TANKCAR PLCX220239 HAD BEEN IDENTIFIED AS LEAKING ONE TO TWO DROPS PER MINUTE FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  ICI WAS CONTRACTED AND ENROUTE TO THE SCENE TO SECURE TANKCAR.  ICI PERSONNEL SECURED TANKCAR BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP.  AT THE SHIPPER'S REQUEST, TANK CAR WAS PLACED BACK IN THEIR PLANT ADJACENT TO THE AVONDALE YARD.  IMTT TERMINALS LOADED THE TANKCAR FOR KMG BERNUTH. SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE, BOB GODFREY,WAS CONTACTED AND RESPONDED.

UPRR RMCC NOTIFIED MR. JOHN JACKSON, MRG. CHEMICAL TRANSP. SAFETY-EL PASO, THAT THE GATX 99157 WAS LEAKING FROM TOP OF CAR AND MR. LEO MARQUEZ - SPECIAL AGENT/HAZ MAT - TUCUMCARRI WAS EN ROUTE.  MR. JACKSON WAS CONFERENCED WITH MR. MARQUEZ UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE. MR. MARQUEZ DETERMINED THE LEAK WAS CAUSED BY A LOOSE PACKING GLAND NUT O THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  THE PACKING NUT WAS TIGHTENED AND LEAK STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: MRG. WILDER, CTS WAS NOTIFIED BY MGR. K. JACOBSEN, DAMAGE PREVENTION, THAT WHILE CONDUCTING AN INSPECTION AT THE GLOBAL 2 YARD, HE OBSERVED TRAILER HJCU 87632 TO BE LEAKING PRODUCT.  HE HAD THE DRIVER TRANSPORT THE TRAILER TO THE SPILL AREA WHERE HE CONDUCTED AN INTERIOR INSPECTION WITH MGR. WILDER.  IT WAS FOUND THAT THERE WERE 10 TOTES IN THE TRAILER AND ALL 10 HAD LOOSE CAPS, ALL TEN WERE TIGHTENED.  NO WATERWAYS OR DRAINS INVOLVED.  THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED INSIDE OF THE TRAILER AND NONE SPILLED ON THE GROUND.  AFTER THE INSPECTION MGR. WILDER TALKED WITH THE PLANT SAFETY MANAGER AND OFFERED TO GIVE A CLASS ON PROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING.  THE PLANT MANAGER STATED THAT HE WOULD PUT INTO PRACTICE A BETTER BLOCKING AND BRACING POLICY TO MAKE SURE THAT THIS WOULD NOT HAPPEN AGAIN.  THERE WAS NO BLOCKING ON THE FLOOR FOR THESE 10 TOTES.  THE LOAD WAS REJECTED AND SENT BACK TO HAVE PROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING APPLIED AND TO SECURE THE CAPS SO THAT NO FURTHER LEAKS WOULD OCCUR.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: MIKE JOHNSON, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, WAS CONTACTED BY REGIONAL MANAGER CTS MARK REIMERS CONCERNING AN UNKNOWN TANK CAR WHICH WAS LEAKING INSIDE OF THE COUNCIL BLUFFS YARD.  THE LOCATION AND IDENTIFICATION NUMBER WERE UNKNOWN.  MR. REIMERS REQUESTED THAT MR JOHNSON RESPOND. WHILE ENROUTE, MGR. JOHNSON, RECEIVED A REPORT THAT TANKCAR SHPX202464 WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AT A HALF A CUP PER HOUR.  DAN SCHULTZE DIRECTOR OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS, LOCKED OUT THE TRACK TO ISOLATE THE TANK CAR.  MRG JOHNSON REQUESTED THAT LEE HAMMOND, MANAGER "E" FIELD OPERATIONS BE NOTIFIED AND RESPOND TO THE SCENE UNTIL MGR. JOHNSON'S ARRIVAL. ANNETTE MCCLELLAND, ETHANOL TEAM LEADER, CARGILL INC. CALLED AND WAS CONFERENCED IN WITH MGR JOHNSON.  MS. MCCLELLAND REPORTED UNION TANK CO WAS RESPONDING TO REPAIR THE CAR.  AT THE SAME TIME, MR HAMMOND HAD ARRIVED AND PLACED A BUCKED UNDER THE LEAKING VALVE TO CONTAIN THE LEAK.  UPON INSPECTION, UNION TANK CO ADVISED THE VALVE WAS DEFECTIVE INTERNALLY AND THE LOAD WOULD NEED TO BE TRANSFERRED. CARGILL, THE SHIPPER, ARRANGED FOR TRANSFER TRUCKS TO TRANSFER THE CAR.  TWO TRANSFER TRUCKS FROM WYNNE TRANSPORTATION SERVICES BEGAN TRANSFERRING THE LOAD AT 16:35 AND TRANSPORTED THE PRODUCT TO AMCO, COUNCIL BLUFFS, IA.  AT 17:47 THE FIRST TRANSFER TRUCK WAS LOADED AND DEPARTED.  THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED WITH THE LOADING AND DEPARTURE OF THE FOURTH TRUCK AND THE SCENE WAS CLEARED AT 20:50. THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS THAT THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HANDLE HAD BEEN LEFT PINNED IN THE OPEN POSITION AFTER LOADING.  BECAUSE OF THE SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NO STATE OR FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.

RMCC REPORTING LEAKING TANK CAR ON RIP TRACK EAST YARD SAN ANTONIO, TX.  INSPECTION REVEALED DEFECTING GAUGING DEVICE AND PACKING GLAND. GAUGING ROD BENT.  ALSO ALL VALVES WERE LOOSE AND LEAKING.  ALL VALVE PLUGS WERE LOOSE.  THERMOMETER WELL LOOSE, SAMPLE PORT STEM LOOSE.  ALL ASSEMBLES TIGHTENED AND CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION (HOME SHOP FOR REPAIRS)

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING INBOUND SORT WHEN THE DISCREPANCY WAS DISCOVERED.  THE PACKAGE WAS A WOODED CRATE EXHIBITING ODOR.  THE CONTAINER WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL 2 AEROSOL CANS OF SPRAY LACQUER.  THE LABELS ON THE AEROSOLS CLEARLY INDICATED EXTREME FLAMMABILITY.  THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE PACKAGE WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE FAA FOR INVESTIGATION.  PHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT PAT MILLER/SEA/FAA/CAFSO AT 13:45 (CST) ON 11/19/1999.

column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DISCREPANCY WAS DISCOVERED.   THE PACKAGE WAS BEING SORTED WHEN HANDLERS NOTICED STAIN AND A GASOLINE TYPE ODOR COMING FROM THE PACKAGE.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL AN AUTO ENGINE PART (CARBURETOR).  THE PART HAD APPARENTLY NOT BEEN COMPLETELY DRAINED OF FUEL.  SUBSEQUENT HANDLING ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 30 ML OF GASOLINE. column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: HALF ON AN AEROSOL CAN EMPTIED IN THIS PACKAGE WHEN THE CAP CAME OFF INSIDE THE BOX.  THIS POSSIBLE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS WAS FOUND WHEN THE STATION'S SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST CLEANED UP THIS SPILL. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELINGS ON THE BOX AND NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK WAS OFFERED TO FEDEX.  AFTER THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED, THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING THEIR INVESTIGATION.

THIS PACKAGE BEGAN GIVING OFF AN ODOR WHILE IN THE FEDEX STATION. WHEN THE FEDEX SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST LOOKED INTO THE PACKAGE TO DETERMINE THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR, THE 4 SMALL FINGERNAIL POLISH BOTTLES WERE FOUND.  ONE OF THE FOUR BOTTLES HAD BEEN EMPTIED BECAUSE OF A LOOSENED CAP. ACCORDING TO INFORMATION INSIDE THE PACKAGE, THE BOTTLES OF FINGERNAIL POLISH CONTAINED ETHYL ACETATE, BUTYL ACETATE, AND ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL.  SINCE THESE MAY BE FLAMMABLE COMPONENTS, I WAS NOTIFIED ABOUT THIS POSSIBLE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS. THE FAA WAS CALLED AND WILL COME TO INVESTIGATE THIS SHIPMENT.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELINGS ON THE OUTER BOX AND NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK WAS OFFERED TO FEDERAL EXPRESS.  THIS SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD PENDING THE FAA INVESTIGATION.

THIS SHIPMENT CONTAINED 3 PIECES.  ONE PIECE WAS A DUFFEL BAG (THE ONE THAT LEAKED THE DANGEROUS GOODS).  THE SECOND PIECE WAS A HARD PLASTIC BOX.  THE THIRD PIECE WAS NOT LOCATED IN OUR INDIANAPOLIS SORT CENTER.  THE DUFFEL BAG CONTAINED VARIOUS CONSTRUCTION TOOLS THAT APPEAR TO HAVE PUNCTURED THE 1 GALLON CAN OF LIQUID.  WHEN THE SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST FOUND WHAT HAD SPILLED IN THE BAG, HE REQUESTED A MSDS FROM THE MANUFACTURER.  THE MSDS ASSIGNED THIS LIQUID A 102 DEGREE FLASHPOINT AND A PROPER SHIPPING NAME OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  NOS (PETROLEUM DISTILLATE).  AFTER PROPERLY CLEANING UP THE SPILL, THE DANGEROUS GOODS SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST CALLED ME ABOUT THIS UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELINGS ON THE BAG AND NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK WAS OFFERED TO FEDEX.  THE FEDEX AIRWAY BILL HAD THE "NO" BOX CHECKED FOR: "DOES THIS SHIPMENT CONTAIN DANGEROUS GOODS."  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED AND THE 2 PACKAGES WERE HELD PENDING AN FAA INVESTIGATION.

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)

FILE AB9199, SHIPPER: AMRESCO, AIRWAY BILL #BDC 5931693386 GOT, THIS IS A 5800.1 REPORT ONLY. ON 11/30/99, A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR, IN 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON OHIO 45177.  THE LOCATION OF THE SPILL WAS IN OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SORT FACILITY, PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS, TIM HINES AND RANDY WILLIAMS RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT THEY BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  THEY DISCOVERED A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE.  THE OUTER BOX WAS MARKED, LABELED AND HAD THE FOLLOWING ATTACHMENTS AS FOLLOWS:  THE TOP OF THE BOX HAD AN ADDRESS LABEL, AN ABX ROUTING LABEL, FRAGILE GLASS AND THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS.  SIDE 1 OF THE BOX HAD: THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME (CHLOROFORM, UN1888M AND A 6.1 POISON LABEL. SIDE 3 OF THE BOX HAD : AMRESCO AND THESE SPECIFICATION MARKINGS, (UN4G/Y25/S/98 USA+AP2251).  SIDE 2 & 4 HAD PRE-PRINTED ORIENTATION LABELS.  THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX HAD THE FOLLOWING MANUFACTURE SEAL: TRAUB CONTAINER CORP., 100 LBS, BEDFORD HAS, OH 44146.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS THE FOLLOWING WAS FOUND: 11 X 16 OUNCE GLASS BOTTLES AND 1 PLASTIC BOTTLE.  ALL OF THE BOTTLES WERE PACKED IN STYROFOAM PEANUTS WITH ABSORBENT.  1 GLASS BOTTLE WAS FOUND BROKEN AND ALL THE CONTENTS LOST.  THE ONLY REASON FOUND FOR THE BREAKAGE WAS NOT ENOUGH CUSHIONING MATERIAL. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INSIDE 2 PLASTIC BAGS AND ABSORBENT ADDED AND PLACED INSIDE A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

column168: FILE AB8099 F, SHIPPER:STAVELY SERVICES, AIRWAY BILL #GWD 57254778855 MRR, THIS IS AN UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT ON 11/30/99, A SPILL WITH AN ODOR WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR, IN 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON OHIO 45177.  THE LOCATION OF THE SPILL WAS IN OUR "A" BUILDING SORT FACILITY, PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS, MATTHEW GROSVENOR  AND BRUCE SHILTZ  RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT THEY BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  THEY DISCOVERED A FIBERBOARD BOX EMITTING AN ODOR AND SHOWING SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER BOX.  THE INSPECTION FOUND THE FOLLOWING MARKINGS AND LABELS, THE TOP OF THE BOX HAD NOTHING. SIDES 1, 3, & 4 HAD NOTHING.  SIDE 2 OF THE BOX HAD AN AIRWAY BILL AND THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX HAD THIS MANUFACTURE SEAL, (PACKAGING ATLANTIC CORP., ATLANTA, GA, GROSS WT. 69 LBS.)  THERE WERE NO INDICATIONS ON THE OUTER BOX THAT THIS CONTAINED A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS THE FOLLOWING WAS FOUND: 31 X 8 OUNCE PLASTIC BOTTLES CONTAINING DIESEL SAMPLES.  THESE SAMPLES HAD BEEN PLACED INSIDE PLASTIC BAGS.  ALSO FOUND INSIDE THE BOX WAS A MSDS AND PRODUCT INFORMATION SHEET. THERE WERE 2 BOTTLES PER BAG.  1 ON THE RECEPTACLES HAD A CRUSHED CLOSURE AND THE OTHERS WERE FOUND TO HAVE LOOSE CLOSURES AND LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 32 OUNCES OF LIQUID.  THESE BOTTLES WERE PACKAGED VERY POORLY INSIDE OF THE BOX.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED DUE TO ODOR AND LEAKAGE.  THERE WERE NO OUTER MARKINGS, LABELS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPPER'S DECLARATIONS TO INDICATE THIS SHIPMENT CONTAINED A REGULATED MATERIAL.  THIS SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 10, 1999 PASSENGER DALE ROY ROGERS CHECKED 3 BAGS FOR TRANSPORTATION FROM BRADLEY INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT (BDL) TO BALTIMORE WASHINGTON INTERNATIONAL (BWI) ON SWAA FLIGHT 211.  WHILE LOADING THE AIRCRAFT FOR THE FLIGHT, BDL RAMP EMPLOYEES DROPPED ON OF THE THREE "HEAVY" TAGGED PACKAGES FROM THE BAG CART.  THE AGENTS NOTICES A PURPLE LIQUID SEEPING FROM THE BAG, AND THEIR SUPERVISOR WAS INFORMED OF THE RELEASE. A CUSTOMER SERVICE SUPERVISOR QUESTIONED THE PASSENGER ABOUT THE CONTENTS OF HIS PACKAGES.  HE INDICATED THAT THE PACKAGE CONTAINED FORMALDEHYDE.  HE WAS REMOVED FROM THE AIRCRAFT.  BDL RESPONDED TO THE SPILL AS AN UNKNOWN HAZMAT SPILL AND HAD AN ENVIRONMENTAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM DISPATCHED TO CLEAN UP THE MATERIAL.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, AIRPORT OPERATIONS AND THE LOCAL FAA CASFU WERE NOTIFIED.  IN HIS LUGGAGE THE FOLLOWING MATERIALS WERE FOUND.  SODIUM HYDROXIDE (1 GALLON), SODIUM THIOSULFATE (1 GALLON) POTASSIUM PERMANGANATE (2 FOUR LITER BOTTLES, ONE BROKEN) , FORMALDEHYDE SOLUTION 37% (APPROXIMATELY 10 OUNCES) THE PURPLE LIQUID THAT ACTUALLY WAS DETERMINED TO BE THE POTASSIUM PERMANGANATE, A CLASS 5.1 MATERIAL.  THE CUSTOMER HAD BEEN QUESTIONED AT THE TIME OF CHECK IN AND HAD INDICATED THAT THE PACKAGES CONTAINED "TOOLS".  HE USED THE "TOOLS" TO CLEAN PIPES. THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND THE SITUATION WAS MITIGATED.
column172: Packages or containers checked on board an aircraft by a passenger in addition to luggage

column168: TWO LARGE BLACK BUCKETS WERE PLACED ON A CART.  WHEN THE AGENT MOVED THE CART INTO THEIR AREA THE PAIL TIPPED OVER.  WHEN THE PAIL WAS PICKED UP MORE OF THE CONTENTS SPILLED OUT AND SHE NOTIFIED AIRBORNE OF THE HAZ SPILL.  WHEN WE CAME ONTO THE DOCK AND SAW THE HAZ SPILL THE PAPERWORK WAS PULLED AND ILN HAS WAS CONTACTED JOHN HONDY WAS CALLED, CHEMTREC EMERGENCY WAS CALLED AND THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER WAS TRIED, THE BUILDING WAS EVACUATED AND DOCK DOORS WERE OPENED TO VENTILATE THE TOXIC VAPORS.  SUPERIOR ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANED UP THE HAZ SPILL AND CONTAINED THE PAIL WITH A CRACK ON THE BOTTOM.

column168: DURING THE OFF LOADING OF BAGGAGE IN PHX, PHX RAMP EMPLOYEES DISCOVERED A BOX THAT WAS GIVING OFF A CHEMICAL ODOR.  THE BOX WAS REMOVED AND OPENED TO DETERMINE ITS CONTENTS.  THE BOX CONTAINED: ONE GALLON CONTAINERS OF 100% ACETONE, ONE GALLON CONTAINER OF RUBBING ALCOHOL (ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL), TWO HALF GALLON BOTTLES OF OVT "PURPLE LIQUID" 16 OZ BOTTLE OF CUTICLE OIL, 16 OZ BOTTLE OF NAIL PRIMER, ADDITIONAL 30 BOTTLES OF NAIL POLISH AND OTHER NAIL EQUIPMENT.  IT WAS NOT DETERMINED WHICH OF THE TWO ONE GALLON BOTTLES ACTUALLY LEAKED, BUT THE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS MOIST WITH A PRODUCT THAT SMELLED LIKE ACETONE.  THIS IS WHY WE HAVE LISTED THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME WITH THE TWO TECHNICAL NAMES OF THE ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL AND ACETONE.  SOUTHWEST MAINTENANCE, AIRPORT OPERATIONS, AND THE SKY HARBOR FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE CONTACTED TO RESPOND.  THE ODOR IN THE AIRCRAFT BIN DISSIPATED UPON REMOVAL OF THE BOX, AND THE HAZMAT CREWS WERE CALLED OFF.  THE BAGGAGE AND CHEMICALS WERE RETAINED, AND THE LOCAL FAA CASFO WAS NOTIFIED TO PERFORM THEIR INVESTIGATION.  TWO RAMP EMPLOYEES WERE SENT TO THE HOSPITAL FOR MEDICAL EVALUATION AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE. THEY RETURNED TO WORK THAT DAY WITHOUT TREATMENT.

A PASSENGER (MS JOI WATKINS) CHECKED A BAG FOR FLIGHT ON SWAA FLIGHT #603 FROM LOS ANGELES (LAX) TO NEW ORLEANS (MSY).  THE FLIGHT WAS A DIRECT FLIGHT WITH ONE STOP IN PHOENIX (PHX).  UPON ARRIVAL IN PHX, DURING THE LOADING OF ADDITIONAL BAGGAGE, PHX RAMP EMPLOYEES DISCOVERED A SATURATED BAG THAT CONTAINED 3 CONTAINERS OF FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS.  ONE OF THE PRODUCTS HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY HALF OF ITS CONTENTS (16 OF 32 OZ) INTO THE BAG.  MAINTENANCE AND SKY HARBOR FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE CONTACTED.  THE AIRCRAFT BIN WAS VENTILATED TO REMOVE REMAINING VAPORS AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT CHECKED THE BIN WITH AIR MONITORING EQUIPMENT.  ONCE SAFE, THE AIRCRAFT WAS RELOADED AND CONTINUED ON TO MSY.  THE BAGGAGE AND CHEMICALS WERE RETAINED AND THE LOCAL FAA CASFO WAS NOTIFIED TO PERFORM THEIR INVESTIGATION. TWO RAMP EMPLOYEES WERE SENT TO THE HOSPITAL FOR MEDICAL EVALUATION AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE.  THEY RETURNED TO WORK THAT DAY WITHOUT TREATMENT.

column168: WHILE TRANSITTING THE AA BAGROOM THE TOPS OF 3, 1 GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLES OF 70% RUBBING ALCOHOL LEAKED AND SPILLED INTO THE INSIDE OF A LARGE CARDBOARD BOX FILLED WITH OTHER CLOTHES.  THE BOX BECAME SATURATED AND BROKE APART EXPOSING THE INNER CONTENTS.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED.  ISOPROPYL WAS KEPT IN MIA FOR PROPER DISPOSAL AND REMAINING LUGGAGE WAS REPACKED AND SENT ON.  NO DELAYS RESULTED FROM SPILLAGE OF HDG.
RESPONDED TO SPILL FOLLOWED THE FLAMMABLE RESPONSE SHEET. CLEANED UP WITH FLOOR DRY. DISPOSED OF PER DMP.

THIS PACKAGE WAS  FOUND LEAKING DURING THE INBOUND SORT IN THE LVKA FEDEX LOCATION.  WHILE THE SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST CLEANED UP THE SPILL,SHE FOUND AN AEROSOL CAN IN THE BOX. SINCE AEROSOLS ARE DANGEROUS GOODS, SHE CONTACTED ME ABOUT THIS UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS. THE PACKAGE DID NOT HAVE ANY DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS OR LABELS AND THERE WAS NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK OFFERED TO FEDERAL EXPRESS. THE AIRWAYS BILL WAS MARKED "NO" FOR THE QUESTION OF CONTAINING DANGEROUS GOODS WAS IN THE SHIPMENT. THE "PREWASH" LIQUID THAT SPILLED WAS QUESTIONED AS FAR AS BEING A HIDDEN DANGEROUS GOODS WAS CONCERNED. THE MSDS ON THE "PREWASH" DID ASSIGN A FLASH POINT OF 137 DEG. FARENHEIT TO THE MATERIAL. THIS WAS MEANT AN ADDITIONAL UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS IN THIS SHIPMENT. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED ON THE SAME DAY THAT THIS SPILL WAS REPORTED TO DG ADMIN. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP PER FEDEX POLICY AND THE PACKAGE WAS HELD IN A DESIGNATED AREA FOR THE FAA.
ARRIVED TO FIND A CRUSHED BOX OF CLASS 9- CONSUMER COMMODITY. AREA CLEANED AND SHIPMENT WAS DISPOSED OF.

DERAILMENT EVACUATION GATX 22635 NOVEMBER 19, 1999, PHILADELPHIA DIVISION. AT APPROXIMATELY 1530 HOURS, FRIDAY, NOVEMBER 19, 1999, AT TIOGA STREET IN PHILADELPHIA PA CSX CREW Q41819 SHOVING SET OFF SOUTHBOUND ON WESTBOUND TRACK. TWO TANK CARS (1ST AND 2ND LEAD/SHOVING END) PUSHED THROUGH END OF TRACK AT NORTH SIDE OF TIOGA STREET OVER PASS.  THE FOLLOWING TWO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CARS DERAILED: GATX 22635 SHIPPER: SUN COMPANY, INC. SHIPPER ADDRESS: PHILADELPHIA PA CONSIGNEE: GATX CONSIGNEE ADDRESS: PHILADELPHIA PA COMMODITY: ISOPROPENYLBENZENE STCC: 4912631 HAZARDOUS CLASS: 3 UN 2303 WAY BILL #159983 DATED 11/18/99 LOST APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  UTLX 641790SHIPPER: SUN COMPANY INC, PHILADELPHIA, PA CONSIGNEE: INFINEUM USA OF BAYWAY NJ, COMMODITY: PHENOL, MOLTEN, STCC: 4921598, HAZARDOUS CLASS: 6.1, UN2312, WAYBILL #159982 DATED 11/18/99, NO LOSS OF PRODUCT.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  APPROXIMATELY TWENTY PEOPLE WERE EVACUATED WITHIN ONE BLOCK RADIUS FOR APPROXIMATELY 15 HOURS. GATX 22635 SHOVED THROUGH END OF TRACK AT NORTH SIDE OF TIOGA STREET OVERPASS.  CAR CAME TO REST DOWN EMBANKMENT WITH APPROXIMATELY 1/4 LEAD END OF TANK HANGING OFF BRIDGE EMBANKMENT, LEANING APPROXIMATELY 45 DEGREES TO THE CARS' RIGHT SIDE.  SLIGHT DRIPPING ORIGINATING FORM THE MANWAY COVER NOZZLE AREA, SECURED BY REACT.  NO FURTHER LEAKAGE DURING THE REMAINER OF INCIDENT. AT COMPLETION OF RERAILING, INSPECTION CONDUCTED ON MANWAY COVER NOZZLE AREA BY CONRAIL'S MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND REACT.  REMOVAL OF MANWAY COVER NOTED GASKET IN GOOD CONDITION AND POSITION.  HOWEVER, MARKINGS ON GASKET INDICATED IMPROPER SECUREMENT IN APPROXIMATE 2-3 INCH AREA NEAR MANWAY COVER SAFETY BOLT/HANDLE AREA. GASKET REPLACED AT TIME OF INSPECTION, AND COVER TO BE INSPECTED BY PRIVATE CAR REPAIR COMPANY AT SHIPPER'S FACILITY TO DETERMINE CONDITION. UTLX 641790, DERAILED AND DETRUCKED BOTH ENDS, BUT REMAINED UPRIGHT, ROLLING APPROXIMATELY 10 DEGREES.  NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  CAR RERAILED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT, RETURNED TO FRANKFORD JUNCTION YARD FOR MECHANICAL REPAIRS, AND RETURNED TO ORIGINAL SHIPPER FOR OFF-LOADING.  THE CAUSE OF THE DERAILMENT WAS FAILURE TO PROTECT SHOVING MOVEMENT.

column168: AT 0730 HOURS ON NOVEMBER 20,1999 LIEUTENANT KEITH OAK CREEK FIRE DEPARTMENT REPORTED THE AXLE LOCKED ON A SOUTHBOUND TRAIN AND SPARKS WERE RELEASED FROM THE WHEELS CAUSING BRUSH FIRES AT RYAN ROAD. FURTHER INFORMATION WAS RECEIVED OVER THE NEXT 30 MINUTES THAT INDICATED THAT THE TRACKS WERE DAMAGED AT EAST ELM ROAD AND MULTIPLE TANKCARS DERAILED ON THE GROUND NEAR ELM ROAD AND NICHOLSON ROAD. THE TRAIN INVOLVED WAS TRAIN MSSPR 19. AN EPA ENTRY TEAM DETERMINED THAT TCDX 11085 CONTAINING SPENT SULFURIC ACID HAD RELEASED PRODUCT FROM THE MANWAY COVER BUT DID NOT APPEAR TO BE LEAKING ANY MORE. DON YORK MANAGER SITE REMEDIATION AND DAN HEALY, BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVE RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 11:00 HOURS. LIEUTENANT KEITH OAK FIRE DEPARTMENT EVACUATED CITIZENS ALONG ELM ROAD BECAUSE OF ACID VAPORS GENERATED WHEN LEAKING SULFURIC ACID REACTED WITH WHEAT SPILLED FROM A DERAILED COVERED HOPPER CAR. THERE WERE NO REPORTS OF INJURIES. AT 13:45 HOURS, THE EVACUATION WAS CANCELLED. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE SULFURIC ACID CAR WAS DAMAGED SUFFICIENTLY TO REQUIRE TRANSFERRING. HEARTLAND WAS DISPATCHED TO FACILITATE THE TRANSFER OF PRODUCT TO TANKER TRUCKS. AT 17:30 HOURS, REGIONAL MANAGER CTS MARK REIMERS ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AND ASSUMED RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE TRANSFER AND CLEANUP. ON 11/21/1999 AT 08:30 HOURS THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED AND EXCAVATION OF THE CONTAMINATED SOIL BEGAN. THE CLEANUP WAS COMPLETED BY 18:00 HOURS ON THE 21ST.

column168: MANAGER CTS RICHARD TUFTS WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC DISPATCHER ADVISING THAT A TANK CAR AT THE ALTON & SOUTHERN YARD APPEARED TO HAVE ICICLES HANGING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. MANAGER TUFTS CONTACTED THE GENERAL YARDMASTER TO ENSURE THAT THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE NOTING UPON ARRIVAL THAT THERE APPEARED TO BE LEAKAGE FROM OR AROUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE. MANAGER TUFTS INSPECTED THE CAR AND DETERMINED THAT THE LEAKAGE WAS COMING FROM A POINT INSIDE THE CARS JACKET AND WAS COLLECTING ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET WHICH INDICATED THAT THERE WAS AN ACTUAL LEAK AT THE ATTACHMENT FLANGE OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE TO THE TANK. MANAGER TUFTS CONTACTED THE SHIPPER AND WAS ADVISED THAT THIS CAR HAD LEAKAGE PROBLEMS ONE WEEK EARLIER IN LOUISANA AND THAT AT THAT TIME ABSORBENT HAD BEEN PLACED IN THE CAR TO SOAK UP ALL RESIDUE.MANAGER TUFTS WAS ADVISED THAT THE CAR WAS ENROUTE TO GATX SHOP FOR REPAIRS AND THAT THERE SHOULD BE NO FREE PRODUCT IN THE CAR. MANAGER TUFT OPENED THE MANWAY WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF HULCHER PERSONNEL, WHO HAD BEEN CONTACTED BY THE SHIPPER AND NOTED THAT THE CAR WAS ESSENTIALLY DRY. HULCHER CUT AWAY AN INSPECTION HOLE IN THE SIDE PLATE SURROUNDING THE BOTTOM OUTLET HOUSING AND THE CAR CENTER BEAMS AND PLACED ABSORBENT MATERIALS IN THE VOID TO ENSURE THAT NO MORE LEAKAGE WOULD OCCUR. THE HOLE WAS THEN COVERED WITH SHEET METAL AND THE CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION FOR REPAIRS.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE DRIVER, RICHARD MOORE STATED HE WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON I-81 WHEN HE BLACKED OUT. THE VEHICLE SUBSEQUENTLY LEFT THE ROADWAY AND OVERTURNED ON THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD.  THE CARGO SHIFTED TO ONE SIDE OF THE TRAILER DAMAGING MANY OF THE CONTAINERS.  TEEM ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTRACTED TO REMOVE THE LOAD AND OVERPACK DAMAGED CONTAINERS.  OF THE 80 DRUMS OF MATERIAL ON THE LOAD, 11 WERE DAMAGED TO THE POINT OF NEEDING TO BE OVERPACKED.  IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT AT MOST 150 GALLONS OF RESIN WAS RELEASED FROM INSIDE THE CONTAINERS.  ALL OF THE MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED INSIDE THE TRAILER, WITH NO CONTAMINATION TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  HIGHWAY 81 HAD TO BE SHUT DOWN FOR APPROXIMATELY 6 HOURS TO ALLOW FOR TH UNLOADING AND TO INSURE SAFETY FROM THE FLAMMABLE CARGO.   THE DRIVER WAS INJURED AS A RESULT OF THE OVERTURN AND NOT RELATED TO ANY PROBLEMS WITH IS LOAD.  WE FEEL THE CONTAINERS HELD UP WELL, GIVEN THE SITUATION

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C COOPER MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER IN ROADWAY 5 STALL 112. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF INSPECTED THE 20 FOOT CONTAINER AND OBSERVED A SMALL DAMP AREA (LESS THAN ONE PINT) ON THE CHASSIS DIRECTLY BELOW THE REAR DOOR CLOSURE. WHILE THERE WAS NO ACTIVE LEAK NOTED THERE WAS A VERT STRONG PUNGENT ODOR FROM THE RESIDUE. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. BASED UPON THE CHARACTERISTICS OF THE DECLARED PRODUCT CONTACT WAS MADE WITH APL, P&O NEDLOYD AND ULTIMATELY THE SHIPPER FOR APPROPRIATE PROTOCOLS WHEN HANDLING THE MATERIALS. AFTER SOME DISCUSSION WITH THE SHIPPER IT WAS DECIDED THE LOAD WOULD BE WORKED THE FOLLOWING MORNING. AS THE CONTAINER WAS NOT ACTIVELY LEAKING THE AREA WAS SECURED FOR THE EVENING. THE FOLLOWING MORNING THE CONTAINER WAS OPENED AND THE BLOCKING AND BRACING INSPECTED. THE 2X6 BULKHEAD AT THE REAR OF THE LOAD APPEARED TO BE PROPERLY CONSTRUCTED HOWEVER THERE WAS A 6 INCH VOID BETWEEN THE LOAD AND THE BULKHEAD. THE BULKHEAD WAS REMOVED TO EXPOSE THE LADING. THE LADING CONSISTED OF 55 GALLONS DRUMS ON PALLET DOUBLE STACKED TO THE NOSE WITH NO BILEVEL SEPARATION. THE DRUMS WERE HELD IN PLACE WITH THE USE OF TY-GARD RESTRAINT MATERIALS. THE TY GARD APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN PROPERLY APPLIED HOWEVER THE FABRIC WAS LOOSE AT THE TIME OF INSPECTION. ONE DRUM IN THE FIRST ROW ON THE TOP TIER SECOND OUT FROM THE LEFT SIDEWALK WAS FOUND TO HAVE LEAKED. THE DRUM HAD SPUN IN PLACE AND WORE THROUGH THE TOP ROLLING HOOP DUE TO ABRASION FROM THE ADJACENT DRUMS. FURTHER INTO THE LOAD 3 ADDITIONAL DRUMS WERE FOUND WITH DAMAGED TO THE TOP ROLLING HOOP FROM ABRADING ADJACENT DRUMS. ALL OF THE LEAKING WERE LOCATED IN THE CENTER ROWS OF THE LADING 2ND AND 3RD OUT FROM THE LEFT SIDEWALK OF THE CONTAINER. WHILE ALL OF THE DRUMS HAD STRETCHED WRAP AROUND THE TOP AREAS OF THE DRUMS TO UNITIZE THEM MOVEMENT DURING TRANSIT RESULTED FROM THE SITTING ON PALLETS. ALL OF THE CENTER ROW DRUMS HAD DAMAGED TO THE ROLLING HOOPS FROM CONTINUAL RUBBING DURING TRANSIT. ALL OF THE LEAKING DRUMS WERE PATCHED AND PLACED INTO OVER PACKS FOR SECUREMENT. THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE REMOVED AND CLEANED PER THE MANUFACTURE RECOMMENDATIONS. DUE TO THE EXCESSIVE DAMAGED TO A LARGE NUMBER OF DRUMS ALL THE DAMAGED WERE PLACED INTO A OVER PACK. THE ENTIRE LOAD WAS PLACED INTO A 40 FOOT CONTAINER PONU 302856 AND RETURNED TO THE MANUFACTURE PER THEIR REQUEST. IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT THE 4 LEAKING DRUMS LOST APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF PRODUCT EACH. NO FREE PRODUCT WAS ENCOUNTERED DURING THE OFF LOADING PROCESS AND IT APPEARS THAT IT WAS LOST DURING TRANSIT FROM ATLANTA TO LONG BEACH. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR IN THE PHOENIX YARD. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED HACK DEMPSEY, YARD MASTER, WHO  STATED THE BUCKET TANK CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM, AND THE CAR DEPARTMENT HAD PLACED A SMALL BUCKET UNDER THE CAR TO CAPTURE THE LEAK.  THE CAR WAS LOCATED IN YARD TRACK # 5 NEAR THE WEST END.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED ERI, THE RAILROADS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CONTRACTOR, AND REQUESTED THEY RESPOND A TEAM TO MITIGATE THE LEAK.  UPON ERI'S ARRIVAL, DEVELOPED THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AT A RATE OF 10 TO 12 DROPS PER MINUTE.  THIS  CAR IS EQUIPPED WITH A TOP OPERATING HANDLE FOR THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE, AND UPON INSPECTION, DEVELOPED THE OPERATING ROD AS LOOSE.  FOUR FULL TURNS OF THE TOP  OPERATING HANDLE ERE REQUIRED TO PROPERLY SECURE THE BOTTOM OUTLET AND STOP THE LEAK.  CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER, CHEVRON, DEVELOPED THE CAR HAD BEEN EMPTIED AND RELEASED THE PREVIOUS DAY. PLANT RECORDS SHOWED THE CAR SECURED FOR MOVEMENT.  IT APPEARS THAT THERE AS A SMALL "HEAL' OF PRODUCT IN THE CAR AND WHEN IT WAS MOVED FROM THE PLANT TO THE PHOENIX YARD, THE PRODUCT WORKED IT'S  WAY INTO THE BOTTOM OUTLET, WHERE IT BYPASSED THE VALVE AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET CLOSURE.  CONTACT WAS MADE ITH THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER AND LESSOR OF THE CAR, HIGH PLAINS, WHO WAS ADVISED THE BOTTOM OUTLET REQUIRED INSPECTION AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP GASKET BE REPLACED. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MAD TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSED, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY IN-TERMINAL SERVICES PERSONNEL, REPORTING A LEAKING INTER MODAL TANK AT THE EAST YARD, LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA. DEVELOPED THE IM TANK WAS NOTED DRIPPING LIQUID FROM THE REAR DRAIN TUBES WHILE IT  WAS BEING OFF LOADED FROM AN INBOUND (WESTBOUND) TRAIN ON DROTT TRACK 804.  AS THE IM TANK WAS PLACARED CORROSIVE, IT AS MOVED TO LOT 6 WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ELA INTER MODAL FACILITY, INSPECTED THE IM TANK, AND NOTED APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT POOLED IN THE TOP SIDE CATCH BASIN THAT HOUSES THE MANWAY.  UPON INSPECTING THE MANWAY SWING BOLTS, THE FOLLOWING EXCEPTIONS WERE TAKEN.  FROM THE MANWAY PLATE HING MOVING IN A CLOCKWISE DIRECTION, SWINGBOLT 1 WAS TIGHT, SWINGBOLT 2 TIGHTENED 1/2 TURN; SWINGBOLT 3 TIGHTENED 1 FULL TURN; SWINGBOLT 4 WAS RESTING ON THE MANWAY COVER PLATE WITH THE BACKED OF THE SWINGBOLT NOT ATTACHED TO THE MANWAY NOZZLE; SWINGBOLT 5 TIGHTENED 2 FULL TURNS; SWINGBOLT 6 WAS TIGHT.  IT APPEARS THAT THE BASE MOUNTED SET BOLT FOR SWINGBOLT 4 HAD BACKED OUT, ALLOWING THE BASE OF THE SWINGBOLT TO DISLODGE FROM THE CONNECTION AT THE MANWAY NOZZLE.  CLOSER INSPECTION OF THE SWING BOLT SHOWED THE THREADS TO BE CROSS THREADED AND THE TOGGLE HANDLE WOULD NOT TURN. THE THREADS ERE HAND FILED WHICH ALLOWED THE TOGGLE HANDLE  TO TURN. THE SWINGBOLT WAS REALTACHED TO THE MANWAY NOZZLE AND PROPERLY TIGHTENED.  INSPECTION OF THE MANWAY GASKET SHOED IT TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION.  THE MANWAY WAS SECURED AND THE SWINGBOLTS PROPERLY TIGHTENED.  THE RESIDUE FROM THE CATCH BASIN AS REMOVED AND THE DRAIN TUBES PRUGED OF THE RESIDUE PRODUCT.  THE IM TANK WAS MOVED SEVERAL TIMES TO ENSURE PROPER SECUREMENT, THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR IN THE TUCSON YARD.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED KYLE MAYFIELD, MANAGER, TERMINAL OPERATIONS, TUCSON, WHO STATED THE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT WAS INSPECTING AN OUTBOUND TRAIN IN YARD TRACK 223, WHEN THEY NOTED SOME LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK CAR.  THE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL DEPARTED THE AREA, AND THE ADJACENT TRACKS WERE TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE IN ORDER TO ISOLATE THE LEAKING TANK CAR.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, MARTIN GAS SALES, KILGORE, TEXAS, TO DEVELOP ANY LOCAL RELATIONSHIPS WITH THEIR CUSTOMERS.  MARTIN GAS SALES DID NOT HAVE ANYONE NEAR THE TUCSON AREA, AND SUGGESTED CALLING THE CUSTOMER FOR THIS MOVE, BHP COPPER.  CONTACT ITH BHP MET WITH NEGATIVE RESULTS AS THEY ONLY DEAL WITH RELEASES AT THEIR FACILITY. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED ERI, THE RAILROADS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CONTRACTOR, AND REQUESTED THEY RESPOND A TEAM TO MITIGATE THE RELEASE.  MTO MAYFIELD HAD GONE TO INSPECT THE TANK CAR AND REPORTED THE PRODUCT APPEARED TO BE EMITTING FROM A FLANGE ASSEMBLY ON THE LIQUID EDUCATION LINE AT THE TOP OF THE CAR.  THE PRODUCT WAS DRIPPING OFF THE FLANGE, ONTO THE CAR AND DRIPPING DOWN THE SIDE. ONCE ERI WAS ON SITE AND ASSESSED THE LIQUID LINE , IT AS DETERMINED THE PRODUCT WAS EMITTING FROM THE PLUG CLOSURE AT THE TOP OF THE LIQUID LINE.  THE INTERNAL PRESSURE IN THE CAR WAS RELIEVED BY OPENING THE 1 INC AIR VALVE, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK AT THE LIQUID LINE.  ONCE THE PRESSURE WAS RELIEVED, THE  LIQUID LINE PLUG WAS FOUND TO BE LOOSE AND COULD BE TURNED BY HAND.  THIS PARTICULAR CAR HAS A FLANGED LIQUID LINE WITH NO BALL VALVE IN LINE AS A PRIMARY CLOSURE.  THE TOP AREA OF THE CAR WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, THE PIPE PLUG COATED WITH TEFLON TAPE, AND REINSTALLED.  THE SIDE AREA OF THE CAR AS ALSO CLEANED OF THE PRODUCT RESIDUE.  THE TRACK WAS THEN CLEARED AND THE CONTAMINATED GROUND AREA UNDER THE CAR NEUTRALIZED.  THE TANK CAR WAS MOVED SEVERAL TIMES TO INSURE PROPER SECUREMENT, AND THEN RELEASED FRO MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

DEAN C. COPPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR IN THE CITY OF DOMINGUEZ.  DEVELOPED A LOCAL BUSINESS OWNER HAD CONTACTED CHEMTREC AND REPORTED STRONG ODORS COMING FROM A TANK CAR LOCATED BEHIND HIS PLACE OF BUSINESS.  CHEMTREC TRACED THE CAR AND CONTACTED RMCC. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED ARNIE WAY, OWNER OF SOUTHWEST INDUSTRIES, LOCATED AT 2605 HOMESTEAD DRIVE.  MR. WAY STATED THE TANK CAR WAS ON A TRACK BEHIND HIS PLACE OF BUSINESS, AND THE ODORS WERE VERY STRONG.  MR. WAY STATED HE DID NOT OBSERVE ANY LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE TANK CAR WHEN HE INSPECTED IT.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE LOCATION AND FOUND THE TANK CAR ON AN INDUSTRIAL TRACK BEYOND THE PROPERTY FENCE LINE.  AFTER LOCATING A STREET CROSSING TO ACCESS THE CAR, INSPECTION DEVELOPED VAPORS WERE BEING EMITTED FROM THE GASKET AREA OF THE MANWAY.  ALL 8 OF THE MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE PROPERTY FENCE SECURED.  INSPECTION OF THE MANWAY GASKET REVEALED IT HAD BEEN DAMAGE.  BASED UPON THE CURVATURE OF THE CUT ACROSS THE GASKET, IT APPEARS THAT THE GASKET HAD DROPPED HEN THE MANWAY AS CLOSED, AND EITHER THE SWING BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND TH LIP OF THE MANWAY NOZZLE CUT THROUGH THE GASKET, OR THE MANWAY  WAS DROPPED WHEN BEING CLOSED, PRODUCING THE SAME TYPE OF CUT.  THE RESIDUE PRODUCT WAS HEATING UP DUE TO AMBIENT TEMPERATURES, AND  AS THE INTERNAL PRESSURE BUILT, VAPORS WERE BYPASSING THE CUT GASKET.  THE DAMAGED GASKET AS REMOVED, AND A FIELD GASKET WAS FABRICATED UTILIZING GORE-TEX SEALANT.  THE MANWAY WAS SECURED AND THE VAPOR RELEASE MITIGATED.  DEVELOPED THIS CAR HAD BEEN PULLED FROM THE SHIPPERS PLANT THE PREVIOUS NIGHT, AND THERE WAS NO PAPERWORK FOR THE DESTINATION.  THE INDUSTRY SWITHCH JOB LEFT THE CAR ON THE INDUSTRIAL LEAD PENDING PROPER PAPERWORK.  CONTACT WITH CELANESE LTD, THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER OF THE CAR  WHILE IT WAS UNDER LOAD, DEVELOPED THEY HAD INSTALLED A NEW GASKET PRIOR TO MOVING THE CAR TO DONMINGUEZ.  CELANESE AS ADVISED OF THE DAMAGED GASKET, AND THE TEMPORAY FIELD REPAIRS, WHICH WOULD REQUIRE PLACEMENT OF A NEW GASKET PRIOR TO RELOADING THE CAR.  CELANESE ADVISED THEY WOULD DISCUSS AND CORRECT THE GASKET FAILURE WITH THEIR CUSTOMER. CHEMTREC WAS RECONTACTED AND UPDATED FOR REPORTING PURPOSES.

column168: V2 WAS E/B 165TH ST OUTSIDE LN.  V1, N/B OSBORN AVE, TRAVELED ONTO 165TH ST COLLIDING WITH T2.  VEH #1 WAS TRAVELING AT A HIGH RATE OF SPEED AND WEDGED UNDER TRAILER.  VEH #1 WAS DRAGGED BY VEH #2 APPROX. 115' IN THE EAST BOUND LANE OF 165TH.  AT SOME POINT AFTER COLLISION A FIRE STARTED COMPLETELY BURNING VEH #1 AND THE TWO OCCUPANTS.  THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER ALSO WERE DAMAGED DUE TO THE FIRE.  OFFICER FETZKO OF LAKE COUNTY CORONERS OFFICE DECLARED THE DRIVER OF VEH #1 DOA AT 1.43 PM.  THE PASSENGER OF VEH #1 DECLARED DOA AT 1:44.

TRAILER WAS BEING UNLOADED WHEN THE SPILL WAS DISCOVERED, THE PRODUCT WAS THEN IDENTIFIED. I THEN SECURED THE AREA, I CALLED THE 24 HOUR RESPONSE LINE AND CONSULTED WITH THEM ON THE BEST WAY TO CLEAN UP. I THEN CALLED MY SAFETY MANAGER (NEWSOME) AND CONSULTED WITH HIM. I THEN CALLED THE SHIPPER AND TALKED TO LEROY CARMEN AND INFORMED HIM HE HAD A DEFECTIVE FITTING ON ONE OF HIS TOTES. THE TOTE WAS PLACED IN OS&D, THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM. I AM AWAITING A NEW FITTING FROM THE SHIPPER, THEN THE PRODUCT WILL BE SHIPPED TO IT'S DESTINATION.

column168: ON 11-29-99 AT APPROXIMATELY 3:00 P.M., BILL GOULDING WAS MAKING A DELIVERY TO FLASH FOODS #118 IN MILLEDGEVILLE, GEORGIA.  MR. GOULDING HAD TURNED IN OFF OF JEFFERSON STREET AND WAS ATTEMPTING TO CIRCLE AROUND BEHIND THE STORE TO MAKE A DELIVERY.  MR. GOULDING TRIED TO TURN ONTO A VERY SMALL LANE BEHIND THE STORE WHEN THE TRAILER STRUCK A METAL TRASH DUMPSTER CAUSING EXTENSIVE DAMAGE TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TANKER.  THE TANKER COMPARTMENT RUPTURED SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 400 GALLONS OF EXXON PREMIUM GASOLINE ON SITE.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT RAN INTO A PIPE CULVERT FOR APPROXIMATELY 15 FEET.  THEN IT RAN UNDER THE ROADWAY IN A DRY DIRT BASIN. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT CORPORATION WERE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED.  NEXT, STEVE FALES WITH FUEL SOUTH WAS NOTIFIED AND HE IN TURN CALLED HANK SIRMANS WITH FLASH FOODS.  MR. GOULDING USED VERY POOR JUDGMENT IN TRYING TO DRIVE DOWN A LANE WHICH IS TO NARROW FOR A CAR, MUCH LESS A GASOLINE TRANSPORT.  MR.  GOULDING WAS TERMINATED FOR HIS LACK OF GOOD JUDGMENT IN THIS MATTER.  AT THE FOLLOWING SAFETY MEETING, STEVE FALES ADDRESSED THE INCIDENT WITH ALL DRIVERS AND REITERATED HOW IMPORTANT IT IS TO USE GOOD JUDGMENT AND TO ASK THE APPROPRIATE DISPATCHER IF QUESTIONS ARISE.

column62: Dropped; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: CHEMICALS ARE NOW STORED ON SITE WITH NO MOTOR VEHICLE TRANSPORT BY BURKE PERSONNEL.  IT IS DELIVERED TO THE 1516 SOUTH "D" AVE.  PLANT BY THE MANUFACTURER OF THE CHEMICAL.  ON 10 NOVEMBER, 1999, AT APPROXIMATELY 1910 HRS, THE SHERIFF'S OFFICE RECEIVED A REPORT OF A WATER TANK THAT FELL OFF A TRUCK ON SOUTH 11TH STREET NEAR D AVENUE IN NEVADA.  NEVADA POLICE ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 1914 HRS, THEY DISCOVERED THE TANK CONTAINED APPROXIMATELY 110 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID AND THAT IT HAD RUPTURED AND SPILLED ONTO 11TH STREET.  POLICE IMMEDIATELY REQUESTED THE NEVADA FIRE DEPARTMENT TO ASSIST. PRODUCT WAS OWNED, AND DRIVER WAS EMPLOYED BY BURKE CORPORATION.  UPON ARRIVAL OF THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, INCIDENT COMMAND WAS ESTABLISHED, AND DECISION MADE TO REQUEST THE DES MOINES HAZMAT TEAM, AMES HAZMAT, AND EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT. INITIALLY A ONE BLOCK AREA WAS EVACUATED.  LATER WHEN THE CONCENTRATION WAS FOUND TO BE 65% SULFURIC ACID, THE EVACUATION AREA WAS INCREASED TO 2 BLOCKS INVOLVING APPROXIMATELY 20 RESIDENTS.  GATES HALL WAS DESIGNATED A SHELTER FOR EVACUEES, AND CITY STAFF AND RED CROSS WERE REQUESTED TO ASSIST THE EVACUEES.  IT WAS LATER REPORTED THAT APPROXIMATELY 10 EVACUEES UTILIZED THE SHELTER.  BURKE CORPORATION (CHUCK BOND) NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND THE DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES WITH ASSISTANCE FROM EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT (LEPC).  DNR WAS ESPECIALLY HELPFUL WITH INFORMATION REGARDING THE NEUTRALIZING AGENT RECOMMENDATIONS AND ADDRESSING THE CONCERN OVER THE ESTIMATED 15-20 GALLONS WHICH SPILLED INTO THE STORM SEWER.  BURKE CORPORATION AND LOCAL BUSINESSES ASSISTED IN OBTAINING BAKING SODA AND HYDRA-LIME THAT WAS APPLIED BY THE HAZMAT TEAM TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID, AS PER INSTRUCTIONS FROM DAVE PERRY, DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES. APPROXIMATELY 1100 POUNDS OF BAKING SODA AND 350 POUNDS OF HYDRA LIME WERE APPLIED TO THE MATERIAL ON THE ROAD.  PH WAS TESTED AND DETERMINED TO BE 8, AND THE SOLUTION WAS THEN WASHED INTO THE STORM SEWER BY FIRE FIGHTERS & THE HAZMAT TEAM.  INCIDENT WAS TERMINATED AT APPROXIMATELY 2248 HRS. AND RESIDENTS WERE THEN ALLOWED TO RETURN TO THEIR HOMES.  DOT IS INVESTIGATING CONCERNS OVER PLACARDING, TRANSPORT, LICENSING, AND CONTAINER MARKINGS.
